	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				The best thing that ever happened to everquest; they made it more like Dark Age of Camelot ;)<BR>
<BR>
Seriously though...guys, it's a different game than EQ1.  As long as people keep paying for EQ1, they'll keep it up.<BR>
<BR>
While EQ's population stays pretty high, you have to remember something...everytime one old player quits, a new one starts.  With the introduction of a new product, many of the old EQ1 players that quit, along with current EQ players, new EQ players, players of other MMORPG's, etc., will try it out.  It's financially smart for Verant.  And, people who still wanna play old skool EQ can still play it.  Heck, maybe eventually they'll mark the price of it down.<BR>
<BR>
*But this is ludicrous!!!  I spent (insert rediculous amount of hours played here) building my character up!  I'm level 60!  I'd better be able to transfer my character*<BR>
---Hold on, bub.  Are you forgetting:<BR>
1) There's a possibility of a new race or two.  There's also the possibility of a few of the old races being extinct.<BR>
2) You guy is dead (unless he's an elf)...it's way in the future.<BR>
3) Your class might not exist anymore.  Even if it does, your spells will probably be radically different.<BR>
4) Different level system<BR>
5) Different system for everything<BR>
6) It's a NEW GAME!  It just shares the same name of the old game...<BR>
<BR>
*My items will break?  I camped (insert uber look here) (insert rediculous amount of time here)!  I have to repair my items??  I don't have enough money to buy stuff to begin with*<BR>
---Actually, in EQ2 I doubt you'll have these problems.  Why?  Cause I'm sure that Verant will take the  time to plan out an economy that will actually WORK in this game.  They had no idea at the time...the economy was deep rooted in the game too.  They couldn't fix it without radically changing the way the game works.  Something tells me that you won't see too many Necro's camping the same exact spot everytime I sign on anymore...<BR>
<BR>
*100 levels???  Possibly 200??  What the %#@$ are they thinking.  It'll take me 10 years to get there*<BR>
---Bah, I doubt it.  Anyone who played Anarchy Online could tell you that having 200 levels was a blessing.  You could sign on, fight, get a level, and feel like you'd accomplished something all in one sitting.  I know way too many people who've played EQ and just get frustrated at the leveling aspect of the game and just forget about it.  While it's going to take you 5 hours to level in EQ, and you only get rewards every 4-5 levels if you're a caster, less often than that if you're a fighter, in Anarchy Online (a 200 level game, remember), when you could get new skills depended on how you played as a person.  It was really a decent system.  And, although you didn't get something new every level, you'd get to increase stats which would allow you to use better items, nano programs (spells), etc.  At least you got to pump your guys power up every level.  While the levels in DAOC took quite a bit longer to get than in Anarchy, spells casters receieved new spells much more often than casters do in EQ.  Fighter skills are more evenly distributed too.<BR>
<BR>
What Verant has relized is that if you make a game where a level 1 character can wear the uber loot, eventually the low and mid end stuff will be worthless.  They've also learned the whole carrot/stick principle (or, as I call it, the Diablo II principle).  People who advance quicker and are given more rewards more frequenly (even if they're not as good as the reward would be if they had to wait quite a while longer) are more likely to play longer, have more fun, and, quite frankly be in better moods when they play.  This boosts the emphasis on community within the game, this makes the game more friendly, relieves frustration, possibly leads to fewer confrontations with GMs.<BR>
<BR>
All in all, I think the sweeping changes are mostly for the better.  I think if you'll give them a chance you'll find that most of your anxieties and complaints about regular EQ will be solved.  And, if you didn't have any complaints before, you very well may be knocked back a bit when the product hits.  *Wow, I never thought about that...I like how this works now*...<BR>
The true 2nd/3rd gen MMORPGs are starting to pop up now.  I think we can probably expect some good things comming in the new few years.<BR>
<BR>
Oh, and about the system requirements...come on guys.  It's over a year away.  By the time we're going to have top end 3-4ghz systems on the market.  One of the draws to these games are the incredible relastic worlds.  EQ shows its age, even with Luclin.  Although those pics look like renders...if they're not, I think I'd more than be willing to upgrade my computer for a game that looks even half way as good as that.  And, if you can't afford to upgrade...you always have EQ, DAOC, and half a dozen MMORPG's with lesser requirements that'll hit between here and now.  You'll be taken care of.<BR>
<BR>
Hmm, I've said my peice.  Can't wait to try this game out.  Looks amazing.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
